## Introduction
\begin{itemize}

 \item The Central Bank of Brazil (CBB) is the monetary authority that regulates the financial industry in the country;
 \vspace{0.15cm}
 \item After consolidating, the CBB becomes available part of the data received from the banks (public and private);
  \vspace{0.15cm}
 \item Data about economy activity, monetary indicators, financial market indicators, delinquency rates by product, \textbf{credit indicators}, etc;
  \vspace{0.15cm}
 \item Why analysing this information?
 
 \begin{enumerate}
     \item In 2018, the average interest rate for revolving products (e.g. credit card and overdraft) was more than $350\%$ per year;
     \item In Ireland, it was around $9\%$; UK, $6\%$.
 \end{enumerate} 
 
\end{itemize}

## Introduction

 In this package, I considered only the monthly data of the following \textbf{credit indicators}:
 
  \begin{enumerate}
   \item \textbf{Allowance}: provision in relation to the loan portfolio of the National Financial System (NFS);
   \vspace{0.15cm}
   \item \textbf{Spread}: the difference between the interest rate that bank charges the borrower when lending money minus the interest rate payed to the depositor;
   \vspace{0.15cm}
   \item \textbf{Household debt}: represents the sum of all debts (loans, mortgage, credit cards, overdraft utilisation, etc) over the sum of incomes for all clients in the NFS;
   \vspace{0.15cm}
   \item \textbf{Interest rate}: average interest rate of new credit operations.

\end{enumerate}

